</td></tr></table></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uzenloser.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ZenLOSER</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Disciple</span><br>  Posts: 319<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(9/10/02 3:30:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=322.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yeah</span><hr size=1> You all need to spend a few years administering and running a game like this one: a MUD.  It gives you a wonderful perspective of the other side and allows you to understand what position they are in and why they do the things they do.<br>
<br>
I've yet to see a VI change (call it nerf, enhancment, weid change, etc) that didn't seem justified at the time when putting myself in their shoes and looking back on my experiences.  Sure sometimes they overcorrect and then bring things back in line (cleric proc hammer) but that's natural and no amount of testing can ever stand up to hundreds of thousands of intelligent players figuring out a way to exploit the new change.<br>
<br>
You see, we're better at the game than they are.  We know and practice all the tricks in the book and when a new change happens we think of new ways to combine it with our current tricks or play it off like a prior trick in ways that the programmers and testers wouldn't figure out for months on their own.  Really good QA depts can stop most of the problem but something always slips through.  Then changes to fix the unintended feature are implimented and nerf is cried.<br>
<br>
This happened time and time again in the MUD that I used to admin for and every change that didnt immediatly make one class more powerful caused a section of the player base to be up in arms and claim they were going to quit.  Even then, when we did increase some class's abilities other classes were up in arms about how they desearved an increase more or how they were now outclassed and useless.  The amount of times I've seen this from the EQ community is both scary and funny. <br>
<br>
It's really a no-win situation but as the admins you have to keep going on and move the game in whatever direction you've decided you want it to move.  Some people might quit but others will start up and they won't be mad about the change because to them it's how life has always been.  Verant has the long-view here.  No they don't care about each individual player or really about any one small group.  They try to make people as happy as they can while still holding to what they want to be done with the game and their vision about how things should work.  <br>
<br>
The vision, however, and play balance (as they see it, not as the player sees it) is what is more important.  In the end balance changes may cause some people to quit but in the long run a balanced game holds more players. <br>
<br>
Moreso than that, changes also cause players to evolve and try new things and new tactics.  Forcing your player base to relearn their normal actions and take into account new things (like the new casting mobs) saves more players than it removes.  Sure some people quit because they hated casters now having ice comet but there's a number of people that were starting to get bored with EQ that had to once again learn and develop new strategies to deal with the changing world.  These players may not realize that the caster change caused them to like EQ again.  For them, however, it gave new things to try and new things to do and stimulated their mind and thus relieved their boredom for a time.  Hell even the chance to get mad at VI keeps some people in the game.  Frustration can also ease boredom in an otherwise unchanged game.<br>
<br>
Mostly pedantic crap but...I guess you just have to be in their shoes a while to understand what goes on and how you have to deal with it. <p><BR>
